\begin{frame}[fragile]
\frametitle{Adding vectors and multiplying by a scalar: Example}
\begin{myitemize}
\item
For a dataset, the \myemph{index} \m{i} of the \myemph{component} \m{y_i} of the vector \m{y} might correspond to a measurement on the \m{i}th member of a population, the outcome of the \m{i}th group in an experiment, or the \m{i}th observation out of a sequence of observations on a system.
Generically, we will call \m{i} an \myemph{observational unit}, or just \myemph{unit}.
\item
We might want to add two quantities \m{u_i} and \m{v_i} for unit \m{i}.
\item
Using vector notation, if \mymath{u=(u_1,u_2,\dots,u_n)}, \mymath{v=(v_1,v_2,\dots,v_n)} and \mymath{y=(y_1,y_2,\dots,y_n)} we define the \myemph{vector sum} \mymath{y=u+v} to be the \myemph{componentwise sum} \m{y_i=u_i+v_i}, adding up the corresponding components for each unit.
\item 
We might also want to rescale each component by the same factor. 
To change a measurement \m{y_i} in inches to a new measurement \m{z_i} in mm, we rescale with the \myemph{scalar} \m{\alpha=25.4}. 
We want \m{z_i=\alpha y_i} for each \m{i}. 
This is written in vector notation as \myemph{multplication of a vector by a scalar}, \m{z=\alpha y}.
%\item
%In statistics, vectors are so common that we don't use a special type face to distinguish them from scalars.  
%When we are computing, or writing formulas, we should bear in mind if 
\item
Keep track of whether each object is a scalar, a vector (what is its length?) or a matrix (what are its dimensions?).
\end{myitemize} 

\end{frame} 


